ðŸ‘‰ Kotlin has functions to **get parts of a collection**.

* **slice** â†’ pick elements by index/range.

```kotlin
val nums = listOf(1,2,3,4,5,6)
println(nums.slice(1..3))       // [2,3,4]
println(nums.slice(setOf(0,3))) // [1,4]
```

* **take / takeLast** â†’ first or last N elements.

* **drop / dropLast** â†’ remove first or last N elements.

* **takeWhile / dropWhile** â†’ keep/remove elements until condition fails.

* **chunked(n)** â†’ split list into pieces of size `n`.

```kotlin
println((0..7).toList().chunked(3)) // [[0,1,2],[3,4,5],[6,7]]
```

* **windowed(n)** â†’ sliding window of size `n`.

```kotlin
println((1..5).toList().windowed(3)) // [[1,2,3],[2,3,4],[3,4,5]]
```

ðŸ‘‰ Use these to **slice, split, or group** your collections easily. âœ…


